{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653063"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:42:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:42:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18555"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18555"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.11,0.54,0.14,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11287"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79436"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11287"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18555"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64758"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10820"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26166"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26171"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79436"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe placenta forms a selective barrier between maternal and fetal circulation during pregnancy. However, certain pathogens can breach this barrier and cause congenital infections.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how pathogens typically cross the placental barrier?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Breaking down of placental tissue","Direct penetration of placental membrane","Transcellular transport through syncytiotrophoblasts","Passive diffusion between placental cells","Transport via maternal antibodies"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct mechanism is \u003Cstrong\u003Etranscellular transport through syncytiotrophoblasts\u003C/strong\u003E. Pathogens capable of transplacental transmission typically enter the syncytiotrophoblast cells that form the main barrier between maternal and fetal circulation. These cells normally regulate the transfer of nutrients and other substances between mother and fetus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreaking down of placental tissue\u003C/strong\u003E: This is not a typical mechanism for most pathogens crossing the placenta, though some severe infections might lead to tissue damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect penetration of placental membrane\u003C/strong\u003E: This is uncommon as the placental structure is complex and resistant to direct penetration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPassive diffusion between placental cells\u003C/strong\u003E: The tight junctions between placental cells make this unlikely for pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransport via maternal antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E: While maternal antibodies (e.g., IgG) cross the placenta via receptor-mediated transport to provide fetal immunity, this does not apply to pathogen transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamples of pathogens that can cross the placenta include \u003Cem\u003EToxoplasma gondii\u003C/em\u003E, rubella virus, cytomegalovirus, and herpes simplex virus. These organisms have evolved specific mechanisms to exploit cellular transport pathways in syncytiotrophoblasts.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Transplacental transmission occurs when pathogens cross the placental barrier from mother to fetus during pregnancy.","The TORCH infections (Toxoplasma, Others, Rubella, Cytomegalovirus, Herpes simplex) are classic examples of pathogens that can cross the placenta.","The placental barrier consists of syncytiotrophoblast cells that regulate transfer between maternal and fetal circulation."],"references":["Megli CJ, Coyne CB. Infections at the maternal\u2013fetal interface: an overview of pathogenesis and defence. Nature Reviews Microbiology. 2022;20(2):67-82. Available at: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41579-021-00610-y"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64758"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18555"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64758"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T17:01:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T17:01:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11287"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79436"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level